President Obama met with Chinese Foreign Minister Yang Jiechi in the Oval Office to discuss the U.S.-China bilateral relationship and important global issues. They emphasized the desire to strengthen cooperation and build a positive relationship. They also discussed the international financial crisis, North Korea, Afghanistan and Pakistan, and the situation in Sudan. The President stressed the importance of increasing the U.S.-China military-to-military dialogue to avoid future incidents. They agreed on the need to work together to stabilize the global economy and address global trade imbalances. The President also emphasized the promotion of human rights and expressed hope for progress in the dialogue between China and the Dalai Lama's representatives. On North Korea, they discussed the importance of eliminating its nuclear program and highlighted the risks posed by its missile program. The President also expressed concern about the humanitarian crisis in Darfur and the expulsion of humanitarian organizations by the Sudanese government.